<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[strangenesfreak]]></name></author>
<updated>2007-05-06T18:42:37-07:00</updated>
<published>2007-05-06T18:42:37-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3350&amp;p=24019#p24019</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3350&amp;p=24019#p24019"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[$5800 in MMC5]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3350&amp;p=24019#p24019"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">dvdmth wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />This, along with the $5010 mystery, remain the only MMC5 aspects yet to be figured out (AFAIK).<br /></div><br />Somebody on the NESdevWiki wrote <a href="http://nesdevwiki.ath.cx/wiki/index.php/Talk:Nintendo_MMC5" class="postlink">some theories</a> about $5010 and how the MMC5 supports 2 PCM modes.  The theories were based on the <a href="http://nesdev.com/5317714-digital_sound.pdf" class="postlink">MMC5 PCM sound patent</a>.  Just Breed writes $40 to $4017 and then $5010 at power-up then $00 to $5010.  Castlevania III writes $00 to $5010, the mahjong game that uses the MMC5 raw PCM, and L'Empereur (and probably other Koei MMC5 games) writes $00 to $5010.  Laser Invasion/Gun Sight does not touch $5010 at power-up, but is still stable anyway, so the MMC5 PCM channel is probably at no-IRQ mode at power-up.  IMO, the theories seem to make sense with the patent, but perhaps someone could look much more carefully to see if they have any errors.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3329">strangenesfreak</a> — Sun May 06, 2007 6:42 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
